<subSubSection pageId="291" pageNumber="292" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="291" pageNumber="292">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Putzeys" authorityYear="1846" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Aspidoglossa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="291" pageNumber="292" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Aspidoglossa</taxonomicName>
Putzeys, 1846: 108. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Putzeys" authorityYear="1846" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Aspidoglossa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="291" pageNumber="292" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submetallica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="291" pageNumber="292">Aspidoglossa submetallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Putzeys, 1846 designated by Desmarest (1851: 102). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="291" pageNumber="292">aspidos</emphasis>
(shield) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="291" pageNumber="292">glossa</emphasis>
(tongue), probably alluding to the shape of the glossal sclerite [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="291" pageNumber="292" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="291" pageNumber="292">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="291" pageNumber="292">Twenty-six species (Lorenz 2005: 146-147) in the temperate, subtropical, and tropical regions of the Western Hemisphere, including the West Indies. One species only is found in North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
